crops.description: Seeds presented by James Stewart, La Habra Heights. A fine-flavored South African papaya, pollinized by a plant from the Sandwich Islands.

crops.presented_by: Institute of Paint and Varnish Research, Washington, D. C.
crops.description: Seeds collected by H. A. Gardner and presented by the Institute of Paint and Varnish Research, Washington, D. C., through the Bureau of Chemistry and Soils. A large tropical tree of the Brazilian forests, with rigid leathery oblong leaves 3 to 5 inches long and shining green above. The greenish, ovoid-cylindrical fruits, about 2 inches long, yield an oil known as Oiticica oil, used in the paint and varnish industry.

Seeds purchased through Arthur W. Burrows, American consular agent, Coquimbo. A small papaya 3 1/2 by 4 1/2 inches, with very thin flesh which is highly acid and is used only in making preserves and sirups. The fruit is yellow when ripe with a spicy aromatic flavor and fragrance, but is never eaten fresh.

From Brazil. Seeds presented by J. I. Case Co., through Reginald S. Castleman, American consul, Porto Alegre. Santa Maria. A new type of rice developed near Rio Pardo, State of Rio Grande do Sul, which develops abnormally large ears and is a heavy yielder.
From Brazil. Seeds presented by J. I. Case Co., through Reginald S. Castleman, American consul, Porto Alegre. Rust-immune wheat developed in Rio Grande do Sul. Variety: Fronteira.
From Brazil. Seeds presented by J. I. Case Co., through Reginald S. Castleman, American consul, Porto Alegre. Rust-immune wheat developed in Rio Grande do Sul. Variety: Frondoso.
From Brazil. Seeds presented by J. I. Case Co., through Reginald S. Castleman, American consul, Porto Alegre. Rust-immune wheat developed in Rio Grande do Sul. Variety: Surpreza.
Seeds collected in the Jardim Botanico, Rio de Janeiro, by H. A. Gardner and presented by G. S. Jamieson, Bureau of Chemistry and Soils. For previous introduction and description see 106347.

Seeds collected by Mrs. Thomas Barbour on the road between Ressano Garcia and Lourenço Marques, Mozambique. The "sausage tree" of eastern tropical Africa becomes 30 to 50 feet high, with rough ternate leaves made up of seven to nine elliptic-oblong leaflets; the large claret-colored flowers are in long spikes, and the blunt sausagelike fruits are 12 to 18 inches long.

crops.description: Dwalganup. An extra early strain.

crops.description: Wenigup. A late clover.

No. 2488. A tropical shrub with thick leathery oval-elliptic dark-green leaves and small white flowers in large terminal cymes. It is native to Brazil. Unless otherwise mentioned the following were introduced as seeds. For the introduction of plants see 106371.

No. 2483. Garuru. A handsome tree with leathery elliptic leaves shining green above and 4 to 6 inches long and large yellow flowers. Native to sandy places in British Guiana. For the introduction of plants see 106372.
No. 2493. A cultivated variety.

No. 2490. Cuttings of a large tropical tree with opposite digitately 3- to 5-foliolate leathery leaves, large greenish flowers, and hard-shelled nuts with white edible kernels. Native to northern South America.
No. 2478. Cuttings from a small tree of rather straggly habit with golden-yellow flowers in loose racemes. For previous introduction see 97567.
No. 2491. A cultivated watermelon collected at Bartica, on the Essequiba River.
No. 2449. Bulbs of cultivated plants collected at Mazaruni Station.
No. 2450. Bulbs of cultivated plants.
No. 2480. Kanakudiballi.
